{South opens a major and North splinters with four-plus trumps, game values, and a singleton or void in the bid suit. Here opener cuebids a control before turning to Roman Key Card Blackwood, and the lesson is to stop in five once the keycard reply shows the pair is off one.
[BID 1S] @S @v(open|opens) one spade, showing five or more spades and opening values. A long, strong major is the kind of hand that wants to explore slam if partner shows a fit.
[BID 4C] North splinters, the double jump @v(base|third) four-plus spades, game-forcing values, and a singleton or void in clubs. The short suit guides opener toward judging the slam potential.
[BID 4D] @S @v(cuebid|cuebids) four diamonds, showing a diamond control and slam interest. Rather than blast Blackwood at once, opener shows a control and invites partner to cooperate.
[BID 4S] North signs back into four spades, showing no extra control to cuebid below game. The auction pauses to let opener decide whether to press on.
[BID 4N] @S now @v(bid|bids) four notrump, Roman Key Card Blackwood for spades, asking how many of the five keycards partner holds. With a control shown and the fit firm, opener wants the keycard count before committing.
[BID 5C] The reply @v(base|third) one or four keycards. From the values already in view opener reads it as one, leaving the partnership short of the full set.
[BID 5S] @S @v(stop|stops) in five spades. The answer located a keycard missing between the hands, so slam would be a guess, and the disciplined call is to settle in five.
[show NS] South held \SKQJT86 \H84 \D8 \CAQ84. After the diamond cuebid and the keycard exchange, only three keycards were present — the spade ace and the diamond ace were both off. With two keycards gone, six spades had no safe path, so South parked the hand in five spades for eleven tricks. The auction ran a touch long through the cuebid, but it landed in the right spot.}
